## INTENT-TO-MODE MAP

| Intent | Primary Candidates | Secondary Candidates |
|--------|-------------------|---------------------|
| SIMPLE | simple | — |
| CATCH-ALL | standard, adversarial | — |
| LEARNING | standard, terrain-mapping, deep-clarification | passion-exploration |
| DECIDING | constraint-mapping, decision-under-uncertainty | strategic-interaction, benefits-analysis, red-team, adversarial |
| BUILDING | project-mode, structured-output | — |
| ANALYZING | root-cause-analysis, competing-hypotheses, cui-bono, benefits-analysis, consequences-and-sequel, red-team | scenario-planning, adversarial |
| CONNECTING | relationship-mapping, systems-dynamics, synthesis, consequences-and-sequel | dialectical-analysis |
| QUESTIONING | paradigm-suspension, steelman-construction | dialectical-analysis, cui-bono, red-team |
| EXPLORING | passion-exploration, terrain-mapping | deep-clarification |
| SPATIAL | spatial-reasoning | — |

**LEARNING tiebreaker:** Use **standard** for plain "explain X" / "summarize X" / "how does X work" expository prompts where the user wants a single defensible answer. Use **terrain-mapping** when the user wants a broad survey of a domain they're unfamiliar with ("give me the lay of the land in machine learning"). Use **deep-clarification** when the user is confused about a specific concept and needs the confusion unpacked ("I keep mixing up X and Y, help me see the difference clearly").

